---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import NewsletterCTA from '../components/NewsletterCTA.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="The engineer behind The Foundations of Software Engineering.">
  <article>
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="post-hero">
        <span class="kicker post-kicker">About<span class="dot">·</span>{SITE.domain}</span>
        <h1 class="post-title">Behind the scenes.</h1>
        <p class="post-dek">
          Twenty years of shipping software, these are the lessons learned, and sometimes
          learned the hard way.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-rule"><span class="mark">§</span></div>

      <div class="post-body">
        <p>
          Hi — I'm <strong>Adam McCombs</strong>. I've spent a little over two decades building
          software, mostly as a full-stack engineer and, increasingly, as the person responsible
          for the engineers doing the building. I've written the feature, built prototypes, test
          piloted new technology, built the architecture that aged well, and made a few decisions
          that didn't.
        </p>
        <p>
          Over twenty-plus years I've watched a lot of stacks come
          and go — the language that was going to fix everything, the framework that was going to
          make the last one obsolete, the paradigm that turned out to be the previous paradigm in
          a new coat.
        </p>
        <p>
          What's struck me, again and again, is how little the
          <em class="accent">foundations</em> underneath all that churn actually move.
        </p>

        <h2>Why I'm writing this</h2>
        <p>
          Most engineering writing optimizes for the surface — the tutorial, the changelog, the
          hot take with a half-life of a news cycle. Useful, but disposable. I wanted a place to
          argue the durable stuff from first principles: why an abstraction earns its keep, what
          correctness actually costs, how to read code as fast as you write it, where taste comes
          from when the rules run out. The kind of manual I wish someone had handed me when I
          started.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm not interested in chasing trends or the leading, bleeding edge. This is about
          learning the fundamentals that stick with you, regardless of the hot new framework.
          I'm interested in the
          ideas that were true before it and will be true after it. Those are the ones that
          compound.
        </p>

        <h2>The detour that taught me the most</h2>
        <p>
          I didn't come up through a computer science pipeline. I came up through <em>music</em> —
          Texas State, performance ensembles, the marching band field at six in the morning, the
          kind of obsessive practice where you play the hard bar a hundred times until your hands
          stop asking your brain for permission.
        </p>
        <p>
          It turns out that's most of engineering, too: fundamentals drilled until they become
          reflex, individual craft folded into something that only works if the whole section is
          listening to each other. Good engineering is an ensemble problem. How well does your
          team work together? How are your systems working together?
        </p>

        <h2>What you'll get here</h2>
        <p>
          One essay every other week, sent through <a href={SITE.url}>the newsletter</a> — slow on
          purpose, free, and easy to leave. No framework tutorials, no churn.
        </p>
        <p>
          Just the <span class="accent">foundations</span>, argued honestly, by someone still
          doing the work.
        </p>
        <p>
          And if you've got something to say on this subject yourself — I'm
          <a href="/write-for-us">looking for writers</a>.
        </p>

        <div class="post-end">❧</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <NewsletterCTA />
</BaseLayout>
